Samsung Evo Cards use TLC nands, but they are definitely better than the other ' Value ' choices in the price bracket. According to A1 SD Bench it gives 27 MB read speed and 17.5 MB write speed inside my phone. Which is more than enough. This card is built to withstand elements. If you want exceptional performance,like faster gallery loading times, look at Samsung PRO line up, as they offer excellent Value for Money.Also i might add a note to genuine or not issue posted by many reviewers. As it turns out that you cant register a Micro SD card in Samsung website, you can register TV, smart phone etc. New Samsung EVO cards doesn't have the arrows and you can check if the card is genuine by checking its transfer speeds. Also the sides of genuine card will be white and the fake ones will be black. Genuine cards are made in Philippines also.Last but not least, i too have purchased the card depicted here by many as fake ( The graphics without arrow and white writings instead of grey ) but when i ran benchmarks with that i got exactly the advertised speed by Samsung, Write 12 Mbps and Read 40 Mbps.At least if they are fake,they perform as good as the Genuine ones. Hope this helps

I am always apprehensive when I buy any SD card, there are so many fakes out there. There are many reviews of consumers receiving fakes in this product listing also, which didn't help me. When I received my 16GB EVO SD card, I decided to do some checks myself.Let start with what I received. I received a standard looking Samsung 16GB EVO SD Card package, with nothing popping out wrong immediately. At the back was a sticker stuck on top of some Korean writing, and I saw nothing wrong in that, because the sticker was a regulatory Import sticker, with name of importer (Samsung India Electronics Pvt. Ltd.), Y/M of Manufacture printed (2016/May), Y/M of Import printed (2016/May), and the model code printed as MB-MP16D/IN./IN clearly stands for India, and elsewhere in the web I have come across /CN (China) and /KR (Korea) too. I haven't checked under by sticker fully, but if there was a /APC, it would be for the Asia Pacific market, I see no problems in that, that a /APC product is being converted to /IN product by Samsung.Nowhere is any misleading info. on where it was manufactured, it clearly says at two places 'Made in Philippines' - one on the back side of packaging lower left, and one behind the SD card itself. Nowhere it says 'Made in Korea'. Also, on the internet, nowhere have I found that 16GB cards are not made in Philippines, though some say 64GB are made only in Korea. So I see no problem here too.The writing on my card is dark maroon, instead of the grey, no arrow symbol also, as someone pointed out. But the card itself has no 'other' issues, meaning that the edges are white, the underside is black with the base model etched, serial number and country of manufacture. I am not sure what to make of this dark-maroon vs grey writing.A point to note that my package came with a 'Original Samsung India' hologram stuck on the package, if it means anything.I tried to validate my serial number (the long 26-digit code including the hyphen in between), but it said Invalid Serial code on Samsung product registration page. I tried to remove the hyphen, and even try between Zeroes and O's, but could not validate.Now, I tried to check read-write speeds on my computer. I used an original Samsung SD Card adapter, and having put the micro SD card in it, inserted it directly into my laptop, then run the h2rtestw.exe (ver. 1.4) on the card. There were no errors on the card itself, it had full 16GB (15271MB actually) worth of memory that tested correctly in writes as well as read. The big problem I saw was in the read and write speeds reported by the tool, a measly 10MB/s and 8MB/s resp. (capital B stands for Bytes). I wasn't sure if I was doing it right, because there could be bottlenecks in the adapter, my laptop's SD Card reader hardware, the size of data chunks being written etc. So I put the card in my Asus phone, and downloaded the A1 SD Bench app from the Play store. They turned out to be quite decent: read and write at 79 and 42 MB/s resp.I think I will keep the memory card and not return it yet (unless it starts having problems in coming few days). I removed the 2 starts from the product rating, simply because Samsung has allowed so much confusion still to be out there. I hope this review helps someone. Please give a thumbs-up if it helped you.

The MicroSD card came with 'exFAT' file system, most consumer electronic devices including my mobile do not recognize that file system, so the MicroSD card was not being recognized by my phone. I reformatted the MicroSD card to 'FAT32' file system with "MiniTool Partition Wizard Free" version (Windows 7 was not giving the option of FAT32 file system for formatting), and now the MicroSD card is working fine. Samsung should have given a clear notification/instruction about it on the packet.

Was quite worried about the possibility of getting a counterfeit card after ordering (see the other reviews) as the market is saturated with fake memory cards these days. I was lucky enough to be able to purchase this card from M.P. Enterprises, when only one item was left in stock. Received a genuine card that passed both H2TestW and FakeFlashTest. I highly recommend ordering items from M.P. Enterprises.Now that the genuinity of the card is out of the way, let me give my thoughts on the card itself. When I first decided to buy a 128GB MicroSD card for my Note 4, I had to choose between SanDisk and Samsung. Both are great manufacturers that make products of good quality, but ultimately, I wanted the card with better performance. So I looked at various reviews, benchmarks, and made up my mind.This review: [...] is what finally made me choose the Samsung one. The SanDisk 128GB card rarely crosses a write speed of 15 MB/s, whereas the Samsung card can achieve around 20 MB/s, which is double of what the minimum required Class 10 speed is.While usually copying files to this card, I'd say that the most commonly observed speed by me is around 18 MB/s. This is very good for a card that is advertised as Class 10 / UHS-1. Another reason I picked Samsung is because I trust their performance. My old MicroSD (which I still use in my Droid-4) is a Class 6  32GB card, but it has a minimum speed of 14 MB/s, which is again, a higher speed than what it is expected from it.In the end, the alternative SanDisk 128GB card is definitely significantly cheaper than this Samsung card, and you will get around 15 MB/s write speed with it most of the time, but the Samsung EVO card is definitely ahead. If you're on a tight budget and want a 128GB MicroSD, get the SanDisk card. It all boils down to your budget preferences and needs. I occasionally record 4k video on my phone, so I need all the extra writing speed I can get. This card guarantees a minimum writing speed of 15 MB/s, even manages to hit 20 MB/s, and exceeds the minimum Class 10 writing speed most of the time, whereas the SanDisk one guarantees the bare minimum speed required to be classified as a Class 10 devices.Oh, also, if you are NOT on a tight budget, and want a 128GB card with even better writing speeds, get the 128GB Samsung EVO+ (Plus) card instead of this one. Its minimum writing speed is supposed to be 20 MB/s. Consider that card instead if you're going to be recording a lot of 4k footage. Right now the EVO+ (Plus) card costs only around Rs. 500 more than this EVO card.Samsung Evo MB-MP128DA/AM 128GB Micro SDXC with Adapter

I got this before I got the SanDisk Ultra MicroSDXC 64GB UHS-I Class 10 Memory Card (Upto 48 MB/s Speed) and if they put up the speeds they do mean it. I ordered this from amazon us because of the number of people saying they got fakes and I paid twice what it costs here with taxes and shipping. So it must have been an original.. But I was very disappointed in its transfer speeds. I saw that samsung had like 4 other kinds of sdcards all costing a lot more with much higher transfer speeds and they do mean it. ALL these cheap sdcards gets you under 50mb read speeds and if you are lucky you get 20mb/sec writes.. More like 15 MB with the Strontium Nitro 6 and 18mb/s with the sandisk etc..  This never went past 20mb/s and usually was more like 12-15mb/s.. The adapter was USB2 but even on a laptop directly connected to it with just the dumb micro sdcard adapter the speeds did not improve much and stayed around 16mb/s. The sandisk read speeds are around 45mb/s and this is like 48mb/s. makes me wonder if they are ALL using the very same card and printing different labels on them.I dont know the exact power requirements since the SDcard adapter and measuring meter takes some power and this showed up as using more than a USB2 flash drive (60mw) but less than a USB3 flash drive (80mw or so) so around 75mw or so.. This was a big issue before when they used to take 400-500mw of power during writes so that part at least have advanced a lot in the last decade..Now I was moving some files inside the tab from one directly to another using its file copy function and the device locked up.. Soon after the sdcard itself disappeared and could not get it working again. So the basic controller is not very good either.. If it can brick the drive with just multi tasking. The drive was only like a third full as it took so long to copy files over I got tired of it. And it only shows like 59GB free if you check which comes to just over 64gb decimal..So the lesson learnt is, pay more and buy a faster drive if you care. Even just copying a bunch of movies onto the card so you can watch it on like the phone later on would just take a long time let alone being able to save pictures and videos you are taking on the fly with the phone or tab. The thing is, the samsung EVO+ only costs less than rs100 more and gives you double the read speeds at like 80mb/s but the writes are still under 20mb/s. And the PRO version which actually gives decent performance for writes of over 80MB/s costs 3 times as much and for things like cameras that take HD video you need cards like those since these wont work..So after buying a bunch of SDcards and seeing how slow they were I got USB flash drives thinking they might be faster and I was surprised that they were even slower when using an OTG cable although they were much faster on the computer.. But those also costs much more. Comparing the built in SD memory expansion in my nexus 5x which shows transfer speeds of around 160mb/sec (the built in memory on the phones/tabs are also storage media just like these cards but they use much faster memory, Even the samsung tab's show around 120mb/s.. Another lesson is, you buy the device with the most memory built in if you want the speeds and not depend on SDcards to increase memory even if they charge a lot for a small amount of memory.

Made in philippines is genuine and is mostly sold in Chinese market. That is the reason why there is a sticker printed in English on Chinese text. It is for the Indian market.*I have verified the images in snapdeal and flipkart as well and they are also made in philippines*It gives 14.91 GB which is exactly as advertised because in manufacturers terms 16 GB is 16000000000 bytes but in computer terms it is 17179869184 bytes. In other words computer divides 16000000000 by 1024 to get 14.90 GB I.e 16000000000/1024= 15625000 kilo bytes, 15625000/1024= 15258 mega bytes and 15258/1024= 14.90 hugs bytes.Put 1000 in place of 1024 you get 16 GB.

I had the opportunity to compare the performance of the fastest microsd cards currently available from top manufacturers. All cards mentioned in this review are obtained from Amazon during the last week or two except when noted otherwise.Test Setup:Lexar Professional workflow UR1 microsd card reader was used for all tests except when notedCrystalDiskMark 5.0.2 x64 was used to produce all the test results and was set up with 2 passes and 100MB read/write sizeAll cards up to 32GB are formatted as FAT32 with 32KB allocation unit size, all 64GB cards are formatted exFAT with 128KB allocation unit sizeTest Results (Numbers are Sequential Read, Sequential Write, 4K Random Read, 4K Random Write in MB/s, speeds greater than 10MB/s were rounded to the whole numbers)16 GB AlphabeticallyLexar 633x** -- 88, 25, 8.7, 1.2Panasonic U3** -- 93, 42, 11, 0.7Sandisk Extreme Pro -- 95, 80, 7.6, 2.632 GB AlphabeticallyDelkin U3 -- 93, 59, 11, 0.6Kingston 90R/80W -- 93, 58, 11, 0.6Lexar 1000x -- 90, 57, 10, 1.4 <== the listed productLexar 1000x with Bundled Reader* -- 148, 60, 10, 1.4Patriot EP -- 90, 35, 10, 0.6PNY Turbo Performance -- 91, 55, 6.9, 0.9PNY Elite Performance Lime Green -- 94, 55, 7.4, 1.0Samsung Pro gray -- 92, 82, 10, 3.6Sandisk Extreme Pro -- 94, 87, 9, 3.0Sony up to 95MB/s -- 91, 51, 4.8, 0.9Transcend Ultimate 633x -- 93, 85, 8.1, 1.464 GB AlphabeticallyDelkin U3 -- 94, 27, 13, 0.3Kingston 90R/80W -- 94, 25, 13, 0.3Lexar 1000x -- 92, 56, 12, 1.5Lexar 1000x with Bundled Reader* -- 153, 66, 11, 1.7Patriot EP -- 81, 22, 11, 0.6PNY Turbo Performance -- 92, 54, 6.9, 0.9PNY Elite Performance Lime Green -- 92, 54, 7.5, 1.0Samsung black -- 82, 20, 8.8, 2.1Samsung Pro gray -- 90, 80, 10, 3.5Samsung Pro+ *** -- 92, 86, 10, 5.3Sandisk Extreme U3 -- 92, 88, 5.5, 0.5Sandisk Extreme Plus U1 **** -- 92, 58, 10, 2.8Sandisk Extreme Plus U3 -- 92, 88, 9.4, 2.9Sandisk Extreme Pro - 97, 91, 10, 3.0Sandisk Ultra ***** -- 46, 16, 7.0, 2.1Sony up to 95MB/s -- 92, 49, 5.2, 0.9Transcend Ultimate 633x -- 93, 83, 7.3, 1.4128 GB AlphabeticallyLexar 633x -- 78, 28, 3.3, 1.4PNY High Performance -- 81, 22, 5.4, 0.9Samsung EVO+ -- 82, 26, 5.9, 1,2 <== the listed product, different capacitySandisk Ultra -- 92, 19, 6.4, 2.4* The Lexar 1000x card is the only UHS-II card available and tested, the bundled USB reader has extra pins for reading UHS-II card** Came bundled with a device*** Purchased from a large west coast electronics retailer. This card is a new release and not currently available on Amazon. It is different from the gray-colored Pro card**** old model tested, not the current U3 model***** old model testedFastest Sequential Read:All tested cards were able to accomplish > 90MB/s, with the Lexar 1000x able to take advantage of UHS-II speed when using the bundled USB reader and leading the packFastest Sequential Write:Sandisk Extreme Pro, Samsung Pro+, Transcend Ultimate 633xFastest Random Read:Kingston 90R/80W.Fastest Random Write:Samsung Pro+Best overall:Samsung Pro+ and Sandisk Extreme ProOther observations:Performance and price are not proportional when it comes to selecting a microSD card. Some of the worst performing cards in this review also happen to be the most expensive.Not all 633x cards are created equal. The two cards reviewed from Lexar and Transcend are both marked as 633x but vary in performance greatly.4k video recording using action cams and drone cameras have a typical bitrate of 60mbps or 100mbps, corresponding to 7.5MB/s to 12.5MB/s. All cards in this review should theoretically be able to handle this usage easily.Using microsd card as supplemental phone storage potentially could benefit from a faster card,Best Looking Card (if it matters):Sandisk Extreme Pro: Red/Gold with white printLexar 1000x: White/Gold with Black/White printSamsung Pro+: White/Black with a red stripe and Black/White printPNY Turbo: Lime Green/Black with Black/White print

Samsung microSDXC 64GB Class 10 UHS-I Memory Card 48 MB/s with adapterI was initially apprehensive about this card after seeing so many negative reviews.But I took a leap of faith and ordered it.Seller: gadgets-guru; Price: INR 1475.The product was shipped from Bangaluru to New Delhi, and I received it in 2 days.Month and Year of Import : August 2015.Packaging and all seems original.Checked out the Youtube video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JVJQVuEReFMtelling about the fake vs genuine sdxc.All criteria satisfied for the genuine one, e.g., Made in Korea, text on the packaging and card, shows 64 GB (actual usable is 59.xx GB) when put into PC, etc.Only thing left out is that it doesn't have that grey arrow after EVO, but someone pointed out that it's the new Samsung Card so it doesn't have it.Also Samsung has made changes to the logo, design and packaging; so there must lie the confusion.Remember to buy the ones with the card reader/adapter, standalone sdxc card being offered are fake.Hope that this review reaches the top so that everyone can see it at the first time. ;)And oh, one last thing: Two days later when i'm writing this review the price of the same seller and others have dropped below 1450.Guess, i should have waited for 2 days. :(

* Update after an year use* Not worth. Very unreliable. It's become undetected in the phone and computer. Lost my photos and personal data for months. Very bad product.Item arrived as expected.I am using this in my new phone (Xperia E3) . No complaints. Space 14.91 GBSince this is first card in this phone, nothing to compare with. The speed in general is as good as it was when apps and files were on main memory.I also run the benchmarking on the card on laptop E430 in the built in slot with the card reader provided in the same package.CrystalDiskMark 3.0.3 (C) 2007-2013 hiyohiyo* MB/s = 1,000,000 byte/s [SATA/300 = 300,000,000 byte/s]Sequential Read :  43.401 MB/sSequential Write :  13.269 MB/sRandom Read 512KB :  41.963 MB/sRandom Write 512KB :  3.916 MB/sRandom Read 4KB (QD=1) :  5.686 MB/s [  1388.1 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=1) :  1.327 MB/s [  324.0 IOPS]Random Read 4KB (QD=32) :  5.639 MB/s [  1376.6 IOPS]Random Write 4KB (QD=32) :  0.194 MB/s [  47.4 IOPS]Test : 500 MB [I: 9.9% (1.5/14.9 GB)] (x3)Date : 2015/01/19 20:48:06OS : Windows 7 Professional [6.1 Build 7600] (x64)I believe the Write 512kb is the key as I am working more with medium sized files (Photos - burst mode, apps, few videos)I was hoping better speed at 512kb write, as others have got. But this could be something with the hardware I am using when testing.In the phone, I am not sure about any reliable app to test the speed. I used A1 SD Bench, for two tests:Sequential:  Read 34.02 MB/s Write 10.77 MB/sRandom: Read 14.76 MB/s Write 1.42 MB/sOverall I was happy with product when it arrived, courier and hence amazon. As far as its durability, there are no real surprises here. Samsung states that the cards are water, temperature, magnetic and x-ray proof with the ability to survive up to 24 hours in seawater, survive in temperatures from -25 to 85 Celsius, protect user data from damage caused by airport X-ray machines and resist up to 13 times the magnetic force of home theater speakers.The Samsung EVO family of microSD cards come in capacities of 16GB, 32GB, and 64GB for a street price of roughly $15, $20, and $45 respectively. All cards are backed by alimited 10-year warranty.Specifications*.Model: MB-MP32D*.Type: microSDHC Memory Card*.Class: 10*.Interface: UHS-I, compatible to HS interface*.Capacities: 16GB,32GB,64GB*.Performance: Up to 48MB/s transfer speed with UHS-I interface*.Voltage: 2.7~3.6V*.Environmental Specs:*.Operating Temperature: -25C to 85C*.Non-Operating Temperature: -40C to 85C*.Dimensions (W x H x D): 0.59" x 0.43"x 0.04"*.Weight: 0.017 oz.*.Warranty: Limited 10 yearsDesign and buildAs you can see, Samsungs completely rebranded flash cards also include the microSD EVO line with a new, attractive looking exterior design.The EVO microSD looks identical to its SD version with its white and orange casing as well as vibrantly printed white numbers indicating its 32GB capacity.The Samsung logo lies at the top of the card while the bottom displays thespeed class designation as well as themicroSD card type, which is Class 10, UHS-1 compatible to HS interface. The Samsung EVO card is also packaged with an SD adapter that is simply branded with SD Adapter for microSD. The other side of the card show the 9 connector pins in addition to the model number. The backside also tells us that the cards were manufactured in Korea.Using our Consumer Testing Platform, we measured transfer speeds from the 32GB Samsung EVO microSD card with IOMeter. Sequential posted read and write speeds of 44.4MB/s and 19.1MB/s respectively. The top-in-class SanDisk Extreme Pro microSDXC boasted reads of 90.9MB/s and write speeds of 74.7MB/s while the Samsungs microSDHC Plus 32GB card clocked in at 71.44MB/s read and 20.08MB/s write. The SanDisk Ultra recorded sequential activity at 44.66MB/s and 14.29MB/s for read andwrite respectively. The Toshiba card showed the slowest results, measuring 34.3MB/s read and 12.1MB/s write.When comparing random large-block transfers, the Samsung EVO posted 43.9 MB/s read with an impressive 32.0 MB/s write, the latter of which was surprisingly one of the best bunch. The SanDisk Extreme Plus measured read and write speeds of 85.9MB/s and 43.8MB/s respectively, while the SanDisk Extreme PRO microSDHC posted 87.6MB/s read and 13.4MB/s write. The Samsung microSDHC Plus 32GB hit 67.35MB/s read and the SanDisk Ultra 20.04MB/s write and 43.98MB/s and 2.45MB/s forread and write, respectively. The Toshiba microSD clocked in at 33.1MB/s read and 1.6MB/s write.ConclusionThe new Samsung EVO microSD line isdesigned for the more mainstream demographic of consumers, specifically for those looking for reliable performance with their high-end smart phones, tablets, and cameras. The EVO Series microSD cards come in three different capacities, 16GB, 32GB, and 64GB eachsporting a sleek white and orange design. These tiny flash cards are alsowater, shock, magnet, X-ray and temperature proof.As far as performance goes, the Samsung EVO microSDs are quoted to deliver 48MB/s reads (with no indication of write activity) supporting a UHS Speed Class 1 and Class 10 videorecording ratings. When we put it through our tests, it measured just below those figures with a sequential read and write of 44.1MB/s and 19.1MB/s respectively, while random activity boasted 43.9MB/read and 32.0MB/s write. The large-block random write speed we recorded was particularly surprising, and easily the best we have seen for its class.Pros*.Solid performance*.Great design*.Great PriceCons*.NoneBottom LineThe 32GB Samsung EVO microSD memory card offers consumers great performance at an unbeatable pricepoint, making it one of the best cards available for its class.

After my phone's internal storage was entirely depleted by all my media files, I needed a way to expand it's capacity. I've never bought an SD card for my phone until now and I really wish I bought this when I first got my phone... Better late than never. This card easily and quickly stores my media files and I can access them just as fast as I could through the internal storage. Also, I feel the price for this product feels like a steal for the ample amount of extra storage I'm getting. Now that my phone has it's 8gb of internal storage released, it works much smoother again like it did when I first bought it.The only drawback for me has been that in lieu of the android 4.4 update, I can no longer properly execute apps stored on the card, music files have become read only, and other odd changes have made it harder to manage files in the SD card. A quick google search and I found an explanation that is more informed than my assumptions:"Prior to Android 4.4, any app had complete access to the SD card and what this means is that any app could not only read the entire contents of the SD card, but also had global write access to the card. As such, a malicious app could be in the position to read the information stored to the SD Card by other apps (often called a banking app) or even make changes to the data. This is of course one of the reasons why Google has introduced the change to SD cards with Android 4.4.Apps can now only access a portion of the SD Card now with KitKat, which is confined to each app. Read access is still possible, for example, so that alternative galleries can gain access to pictures. As well, when you uninstall an app from your device, the corresponding folder is now delete on the SD card so that no garbage is left behind."This is not fault on the SD card itself!For those who have phones that don't run Android this obviously doesn't concern you, but just a warning for those who expect complete power over the storage unit on an non-rooted Android powered device.

I was quite surprised to see too many false or ignorant claims about recieving a fake samsung card. As responsible consumers, we are destroying the reputation of multiple brands(Amazon & Samsung) and the seller. But please don't get me wrong as I am not trying to imply they are always right.I use this card and it is genuine and working well for me. It doesn't have any arrow or grey colour printing.I didn't buy it here, but from another reputed online marketplace since I got a better deal there at that time. A little piece of advice from me when buying from Amazon: Always verify the reputation of the seller and prefer the sellers selling through amazon fullfilled badge.I am not going to give a lengthy lecture regarding the pros and cons of the card. It is a good card which is exactly what is written in the product specification and description. I have limited the rating to 4 stars because there are better cards available in the evo series with the same data capacity. But this card is really good and does what it is designed to do, if you got a genuine one.By now, you might've already know how to distingush between a fake and genuine one by looks.Genuine* Better build quality* Better print quality* Edges are white in colour.* Edges are neatly and precisely cut.* Model number is printed at rear side.Fake* Edges are not white* Lower print quality* Lower build quality* Different font thickness* Different colour tone* Edges may not be precisely cut.Some other reviews mentioned about an arrow and the country manufactured for reference to detect fake products. But that can't be taken into consideration as manufacturers produce their goods from different countries in different batches. So there will be variations in different product batches.But the unfortunate fact is that counterfeiters are getting smart these days. So looks can be decieving some times. It is really hard to distingush between real and fake products just by looking at it.Now, if u have already bought this card, let me help you to find whether it is genuine or not.Through your PCDownload H2testw testing tool from the link below.www.softpedia.com/get/System/System-Miscellaneous/H2testw.shtmlRun it on your PC and test your sd card for read and write speeds. If the results shows something close to what is given in specification, your product is genuine.In your android phoneDownload this app from playstorehttps://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.humanlogic.sdiThe app name is SD Insight and it will detect the manufacturer, year, model and serial number of your sd card.(The model no. is shown as all zeroes sometimes. Need not be taken as a concern). If it shows everything as it is supposed to be, then your product is genuine.You can also download the app called A1 SD Bench to do a benchmark test and check the read/write speed of your sd card.https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.a1dev.sdbenchHope this helps.Cheers.
